        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3907319187" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7036345563413279054">Compared to Faulkner, I expect a tour de force, but I was disappointed even if the book finishes brilliantly, the beginning will have been laborious. We follow the fate of a young woman living in Chicago, whose father, a notable from a small town in the South, has just died suddenly. He had recently remarried to a woman much younger than himself. Reunited, the two women cordially hate each other, and the widow surprises the whole town when her family (which, according to her words, did not exist</span>
  <span id="freeText7036345563413279054" style="display:none">Compared to Faulkner, I expect a tour de force, but I was disappointed even if the book finishes brilliantly, the beginning will have been laborious. We follow the fate of a young woman living in Chicago, whose father, a notable from a small town in the South, has just died suddenly. He had recently remarried to a woman much younger than himself. Reunited, the two women cordially hate each other, and the widow surprises the whole town when her family (which, according to her words, did not exist) arrives at the funeral. A novel that explains well the South's bourgeoisie, its codes and its traditions but something missing; so that, as with Faulkner, my mind is totally under the spell.</span>
