  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1669713412" />
    <a title="Claire" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4280724-claire"><img alt="Claire" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1427393997p2/4280724.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1669713412?book_show_action=true">Jun 15, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Claire" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Claire" href="/user/show/4280724-claire">Claire</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780679728832" href="/book/show/386416.The_Optimist_s_Daughter">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1669713412" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5174049139782572056">Achingly beautiful. There is a reason this book won the Pulitzer Prize. There is so much space between the words on the page. You have to do some filling in, and because you have to involve yourself more while reading, you start to merge with Laurel, the narrator. All of Laurel&apos;s thoughts and feelings become that much more poignant and revelatory. The story is also imbued with the melancholy and fatalism often seen in good Southern literature. This short book deserves several readings.</span>
  <span id="freeText5174049139782572056" style="display:none">Achingly beautiful. There is a reason this book won the Pulitzer Prize. There is so much space between the words on the page. You have to do some filling in, and because you have to involve yourself more while reading, you start to merge with Laurel, the narrator. All of Laurel's thoughts and feelings become that much more poignant and revelatory. The story is also imbued with the melancholy and fatalism often seen in good Southern literature. This short book deserves several readings.</span>
  <a data-text-id="5174049139782572056" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

