<div id="review_3077901726" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3077901726" />
    <a title="Kerrin  P" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/7912849-kerrin-p"><img alt="Kerrin  P" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1616101276p2/7912849.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3077901726?book_show_action=true">Dec 17, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Kerrin  P" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Kerrin  P" href="/user/show/7912849-kerrin-p">Kerrin  P</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3077901726" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11480873651338219356">The Optimist&apos;s Daughter by Eudora Welty is an emotional story about Laurel McKelva Hand who travels to New Orleans to be with her father for an eye surgery. Her father is accompanied by his silly and trite second wife, who is the same age as Laurel. Her father fails to recover and dies. Then Laurel and her step-mother must take the body back to Mississippi. Back in the family home, and surrounded by close friends, Laurel must face the truths about her relationships with her parents, her relation</span>
  <span id="freeText11480873651338219356" style="display:none">The Optimist's Daughter by Eudora Welty is an emotional story about Laurel McKelva Hand who travels to New Orleans to be with her father for an eye surgery. Her father is accompanied by his silly and trite second wife, who is the same age as Laurel. Her father fails to recover and dies. Then Laurel and her step-mother must take the body back to Mississippi. Back in the family home, and surrounded by close friends, Laurel must face the truths about her relationships with her parents, her relationship with her deceased husband, her parents' relationship with each other and the bizarre relationship with her step-mother, who has blantantly lied to Laurel. There is a great deal of symbolism surrounding "vision" as both of Laurel's parents had eye issues, visions of deceased people, and also of the lack of vision of her step-mother. The book is 180 pages long and won a Pulitzer Prize for Fiction-winning short novel. </span>
  <a data-text-id="11480873651338219356" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


