  <span id="freeText5812639975908084951" style="display:none">The Optimist's Daughter (1972) <br />Author: Eudora Welty <br />Read: 7/28/20 <br />Rating: 2.5/5 stars <br /><br />A <br />prolonged <br />eulogy- <br />Musings on loss, <br />aftermath of death. <br />evocative writing, <br />the power of memories. <br />Although some parts were eloquent, <br />most felt impersonal and muddled. <br />Awful stepmom and "bridesmaids" talks steal show, <br />main characters left underdeveloped. <br />Trite scenes given inflated meaning, <br />ending that fails to satisfy. <br />Comes with needless nuances; <br />makes it hard to relate-<br />But didactic in<br />Southernisms! <br />Pulitzer? <br />Calls for <br />more. <br /> <br />Title Meaning: Refers to protagonist Laurel, whose father Clinton McKena was forever the "Optimist"- especially when it came to his wife's misfortunes in health. It could be argued that this was merely his coping mechanism and- more accurately- a form of denial, his way of pretending everything was perfectly fine. <br /><br />#Etheree #StackedEtheree #ReviewPoem #bereavement #fatherdaughter #funeral #hospital #inlaws #marriage #NewOrleans #PulitzerPrize #socialclass #Texas #TheSouth <br /></span>
